 <br>
If we are always generating the maximum aggro we can generate (and some may argue that's not very much), how can it be our fault that someone else steal the aggro?  Aggro for everyone else works in a deterministic manner.  If caster X manages to get himself overaggroed doing Y while a warrior is tanking, then that's going to work every single time thereafter too with the same warrior (barring usage of AE Taunt, procs, and success of the Taunt key).  <br>
<br>
Some of you say that aggro is necessary, like slowing.  But just because the aggro is necessary still doesn't make it our problem.  Just because a mob must be slowed doesn't mean warrior can turn on our super aggro mode to compensate for this.  It is still up to the slower or some other member to deal with the necessary aggro because the warrior does not have a choice with how much aggro he puts out.  <br>
<br>
I'm wondering if warrior aggro issues just comes from other classes not understanding how we get our aggro.  I have been in groups where people will complain I'm not taunting enough, even though this makes no sense since it's not up to me to decide how often Taunt succeeds.  Maybe the other classes think we can somehow get more aggro if we only try harder?  That is true for every non pure melee.  If you play smarter, you can usually get more aggro via spells (sometimes trivially, like Rangers and Paladins).  But not for us.  Our aggro is fixed.  It doesn't matter if that mob must be slowed or whatever, there is nothing more we can help.  Does every group really know this?  I don't have problems holding taunt, but I have been in plenty of pickup groups that'd say something like, 'Wow you hold aggro well our last warrior sucked&quot;.  But isn't that a silly thing to say?  It's not like my taunt somehow works more often than the last warrior because I'm pressing it in a secret technique.  Our aggro comes from our gear, and if it's not enough it will never be enough no matter how hard we try.  We know this, but does everyone else know?  I used to think yes, but now I'm not so sure.<br>
<br>
And if that's the case, then it can explain the problem pretty well.  If your group believes you can actually do anything to effect the aggro you generate (aside from weapon choices), it's no wonder the pickup groups think warriors suck.  The average LFG warrior in say PoV certainly lacks the gear that can effectively deal with initial slow aggro (probably the biggest compliant for warriors), and he will never be able to deal with the slow aggro effectively unless the group understands his weakness and compensates for this.   <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=468916">Phantron</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kilaara>Kilaara</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 215<br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/6/03 2:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2872.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Is the warrior problem just a matter of midunderstanding</span><hr size=1> Thats it Phantron.<br>
